><gtr:role><gtr:name>FELLOW</gtr:name></gtr:role><gtr:role><gtr:name>PRINCIPAL_INVESTIGATOR</gtr:name></gtr:role></gtr:roles></gtr:personRole></gtr:personRoles><gtr:project url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/projects?ref=ES%2FF034164%2F1"><gtr:id>B7ADDE50-DCFC-4AF4-9524-35FDBB22FA71</gtr:id><gtr:title>Inequality, economic segregation, and school achievement</gtr:title><gtr:status>Closed</gtr:status><gtr:grantCategory>Fellowship</gtr:grantCategory><gtr:grantReference>ES/F034164/1</gtr:grantReference><gtr:abstractText>During the two years of the post-doctoral fellowship, Dr Lugo will develop a theoretical model capable of explaining the effect of socio-economic segregation and inequality on children?s performance at school. This study is motivated by the finding that, in the context of Argentina, economic segregation unambiguously worsens the academic achievement of poor students (while does not deteriorate that of non-poor) and increases the disparities in performance between poor and non-poor pupils. The results were obtained using year-to-year school variations and classes-within-school variations at a given point in time. The research will be based on existing models of social distances, where the allocation of children across schools on socio-economic grounds is incorporated.
